</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Connie Johnson 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"If we pray together, maybe we can stay together," El DeBarge earnestly sings 
on one track in a manner that recalls Marvin Gaye's classic "What's Going On." 
The Gaye influence has always been obvious in this singer-songwriter's music, 
and "Gemini" sounds like Gaye-meets-Guy, especially on the aggressively sexy 
"Real Love" and the even more blatantly amorous "Make You Mine." Where there 
once was an element of boyish sweetness to DeBarge's delivery, there's some 
very adult-sounding regret and resolution to his voice on such tracks as "Turn 
the Page" and "Broken Dreams." The religious references on the latter cut may 
be there in order to defuse -- or excuse -- the raw sexuality that appears 
elsewhere on the album. But, of course, it's precisely that type of 
contradiction that always made Gaye such a complex and interesting artist. 
Connie Johnson 
</P>
